{{Essay|date=August 2009}}
[[Mass media]] influences spatial [[perception]] through journalistic [[cartography]] and spatial [[bias]] in news coverage.

"[[Journalism]] is one of the few industries that provide the [[general public]] the most of its [[information]] about places and [[geography]],",<ref>Monmonier, M.,(1989). Maps with the news. Chicago: The university Chicago Press, p.1</ref> mass media is one of the significant factors in shaping perception of places.<ref name=lewis>Lewis, L., Degani, A., Hudson., (1980). The measurement and explanation of the spatial perception of Africa: a Nigerian viewpoint. [[Geografiska Annaler]], 62B, 33-38</ref><ref>Gribok, M. V., (2008). Cartographic representation of mass media influence on the formation of the image of Russian regions. Vestnik Moskovskogo Universiteta, 5 (4), 41-46.</ref> Moreover, mass media has been criticized for "limited [[iconography]] that constructs the newscape-generic locations that are interchangeable from story to story, and which have come to give a restrictive and distorted worldview".<ref>Huxford, J., (2007). The proximity paradox: Live reporting, virtual proximity and the concept of place in the news. Journalism. 8, p.670.</ref> Lack of geographical balance in news coverage may lead to limitations of spatial knowledge, i.e., US media focuses on a limited number of nations and regions for international news coverage.<ref>Golan, G., & Wanta, W., (2003). International elections on the U.S. network news: An examination of factors affecting newsworthiness. Gazette,. 65, 25-39.</ref>

When some news has an important geographic component, [[journalism]] concerns with a location of journalistic information.<ref name="Monmonier, M. 1989">Monmonier, M., (1989). Maps with the news. Chicago: The university of Chicago press.</ref> Use of maps becomes appropriate as "a map is an efficient means for showing location and describing geographic relationships".<ref>Monmonier, M., (1989). Maps with the news. Chicago: The university of Chicago press, p.1</ref> Mass media may use maps to show an event that have spatially distributed data like election results, the distribution of [[acid rain]], radon contamination, weather forecast, traffic, or traveling routes; also describe a story of a battle, a geopolitical strategy, or an environmental threat.<ref name="Monmonier, M. 1989"/> Geographers criticize journalistic cartography for deficiencies and constraints of map production.<ref>Gilmartin, P., (1985). The design of journalistic maps/purposes, parameters and prospects. Cartographica: The international journal for geographic information and geovisualization, 22, 1-18.</ref><ref name="Green, D. R. 1999">Green, D. R., (1999). Journalistic cartography: good or bad? A debate point. The cartographic journal, 36, 141-153.</ref> Maps in journalism are produced by graphic artists, who lack in cartographic training.<ref name="Green, D. R. 1999"/> 

Geographers have explored the spatial bias in news reporting.<ref>Hoare, A., (1991). Making the news: spatial and non-spatial biases in British parliamentary reports of the Rowntree - Mackintosh takeover. [[Geografiska Annaler]], 73B, 95-109.</ref><ref>Walmsley, D. J., (1980). Spatial bias in Australian news reporting. [[Australian Geographer]], 14, 342-349.</ref> Spatial pattern of news is created by journalistic norms, which concern is national coverage, national interest, geographic stereotypes and accessibility to news events.<ref name="Brooker-Gross, S. 1983">Brooker-Gross, S., (1983). Spatial aspects of newsworthiness. [[Geografiska Annaler]], 65B, 1-9.</ref> As mass media provides live reporting from the scenes of the news events, journalism requires spatial proximity, event proximity, and [[broadcast]] proximity.<ref>Huxford, J., (2007). The proximity paradox: Live reporting, virtual proximity and the concept of place in the news. Journalism. 8, 657-674.</ref> Capitals, major financial centers and politically unstable places are highly geographically stereotyped and considered as newsworthy locations where important events happen often <ref name=lewis/><ref name="Brooker-Gross, S. 1983"/> Economic ties and [[social distance]] play also significant role in news coverage.<ref>Bendix, J., & Liebler, C. M., (1999). Place, distance, and environmental news: geographic variation in newspaper coverage of the spotted owl conflict. Annals of the Association of American geographers, 89(4), 658-676.</ref><ref>Tichenor, P.J., Donohue, G.A., Olien, C.N. (1980). Community conflict and the press. Beverly Hills, CA: Sage.</ref><ref>Dunwoody, S., & Griffin, R.J. (1993). Journalistic strategies for reporting long-term environmental issues: a case study of three superfund sites. In A. Hansen (Ed.), The mass media and environmental issues, (pp. 22-50). Leicester, England: Leicester University Press.</ref>

